Mastering keyboard shortcuts is one of the fastest ways to boost your productivity as an administrative professional. Moving your hand from the keyboard to the mouse hundreds of times a day creates "micro-latencies" that add up to hours of lost time each month.

Here are 25 essential shortcuts categorized by how youâ€™ll likely use them.
Navigation and Selection

These help you zip through long documents or emails without touching the mouse.

    Ctrl + Left/Right Arrow: Move the cursor one full word at a time.

    Ctrl + Up/Down Arrow: Move the cursor to the beginning of the previous or next paragraph.

    Ctrl + Home: Jump to the very top of a document or page.

    Ctrl + End: Jump to the very bottom of a document or page.

    Shift + Home/End: Select all text from the cursor to the start or end of the line.

    Ctrl + Shift + Home/End: Select all text from the cursor to the start or end of the entire document.

    Ctrl + A: Select all content in the current window.

Efficient Editing

For when you are drafting reports, meeting minutes, or correspondence.

    Ctrl + Backspace: Delete the entire word to the left of the cursor.

    Ctrl + Delete: Delete the entire word to the right of the cursor.

    Ctrl + Z: Undo your last action (the ultimate lifesaver).

    Ctrl + Y: Redo an action you just undid.

    Ctrl + K: Highlight text and press this to quickly insert a hyperlink.

    Ctrl + F: Find a specific word or phrase within a document or webpage.

    Ctrl + H: Find and Replace (perfect for updating a name or date across a whole document).

Window & Task Management

As an admin, you likely have dozens of tabs and apps open. Use these to stay organized.

    Alt + Tab: Toggle between your open applications.

    Windows + D: Instantly hide everything and show your Desktop.

    Windows + Left/Right Arrow: Snap your current window to one side of the screen (great for data entry from one window to another).

    Windows + E: Open File Explorer to find documents quickly.

    Windows + V: Open your Clipboard History. This allows you to see the last several things you copied, not just the most recent one.

    Windows + Shift + S: Take a partial screenshot to quickly grab a specific error message or snippet of info to send in a chat.

Quick Formatting & Systems

    Ctrl + B / I / U: Bold, Italicize, or Underline.

    Ctrl + S: Save your work (do this habitually!).

    Ctrl + P: Bring up the Print menu.

    Windows + L: Lock your computer instantly (essential for privacy when stepping away from your desk).

    Ctrl + Shift + Esc: Open the Task Manager directly if a program freezes.

    Pro Tip: If you frequently use Windows + V, you can "pin" items to your clipboard (like a company address or a standard email sign-off) so they are always available to paste, even after you restart your computer.

